The paper deals with the problem of computing the partition function of two-state spin systems on a bounded degree graph, which involves algorithms and computational complexity. Therefore, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also discusses the self-avoiding tree, which is a combinatorial object, and presents an FPTAS (Fully Polynomial-Time Approximation Scheme), which involves approximation algorithms, making cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) likely sub-categories as well. Finally, the paper discusses the strong correlation decay property of the systems, which is a statistical physics concept, making cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) a possible sub-category.
